Let me leave you with this notion: Unless you can enforce it, you have no solution. This is the primary reason that the Quellious Quarters calendar ultimately failed. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=bonishortfoot>Boni Shortfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(2/24/02 3:48:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=203.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Solution based on VI rules</span><hr size=1> I don't mean to rain on anybody's parade, but VI has already set policies to govern player behavior/actions.  It's well meaning to want to create rules of conduct outside of the policies already set forth by VI, but VI will not support it. Things such as calendars, lists, how long you've been at a spawn, camp checks, claiming spawns, etc. do not exist when it comes to their decisions.  <br>
<br>
This is a reality check :P<br>
<br>
Guides and GMs use the Play Nice Policies to govern how players are expected to behave in game.  These are the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> only</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> things that will be looked at in terms of VI's final decision on arbitration.  I know we'd all like play according to our own rules we've set forth and agreed on, but VI will not support those player made rules since we're &quot;In Their World Now&quot;.<br>
<br>
I think what would be more appropriate would be to look over the Play Nice Policies again and use them to guide our behavior.  Sure there are grey areas, but we should be able to reach agreement over any sort of issues that come before us in the future.<br>
<br>
After the Play Nice Policies, I've given an example of a potential Ragefire situation and how the Play Nice Policies can be used to our benefit rather than seen as a stumbling block or something we have to go around.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1.1 Play Nice Policies - Activity within EverQuest </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
In addition to the general guidelines listed in section 1.0, players are also subject to these supplementary rules while playing EverQuest. While by no means an all-inclusive list of the do's and don'ts in EverQuest, it provides a suitable foundation by which the player can determine what activities are appropriate: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> You may not steal kills.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Kill Stealing is defined as the killing of an NPC for any reason that is already fighting or pursuing another player or group without that group's specific permission.  The intent of this rule is discourage and make note of habitual Kill Stealers, not to punish those who honestly try to work together or those who make an honest mistake. Its enforcement by the EverQuest Customer Service Staff will reflect this philosophy. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> You may not ninjaloot.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Ninjalooting is defined as taking special equipment from a fallen creature without the express permission of those who killed the creature if they are in attendance.  The purpose of this rule is to stop those who stand near creatures that carry special items and attempt loot that equipment prior to it being looted by the rightful owner.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> *You must comply with arbitration for contested spawns.*</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
There are cases where two or more groups wish to kill the same thing. In these cases, the groups are required to compromise. If an equitable compromise cannot be reached between the players prior to EverQuest Customer Service Staff involvement, the EQCSR will mandate a binding compromise. Refusing to abide by a compromise mandated by an EQCSR will be considered disruption. It is therefore strongly suggested that the groups make every attempt to reach a compromise that they can live with prior to involving an EQCSR, who may mandate a compromise that does not suit you to the extent that a player-devised compromise would.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Note: A &quot;group&quot; in this case is defined as a party of one or more characters that are united in a common belief or goal and are <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> capable</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of completing that goal.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> You may not disrupt the normal playability of a zone or area.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Zone/Area Disruption is defined as any activity designed to harm or inconvenience a number of groups rather than a specific player or group of players. This includes things such as:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Monopolizing most or all of the kills in an area. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Deliberately blocking a doorway or narrow area so other players cannot get past. <br>
Refusing to cooperate with the other parties at a contested spawn site after having been instructed to do so by an EQCSR. <br>
Making excessive and inappropriate use of zone-wide communications (/shout, /ooc, /auction). <br>
</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Ragefire example:<br>
<br>
1) Player-devised Compromise: Ragefire (the human) spawns.  Two or more groups wish to kill him.  The groups are required to compromise.  Both groups/parties are under the definition of &quot;group&quot; (united in a common belief/goal and capable of completing it).  So, one of the grey areas within these policies is the term &quot;capable&quot;.  Deeming who is capable in completing the goal (killing Ragefire) and who is not, is arbitrary since it is based upon opinion.  The word moot comes to mind.  There is no pre-determined minimum amount of players necessary to kill Ragefire.  Example: It could take one group to six groups or more to kill him.  Therefore, each spawn situation is independent.  There is no carry-over to other future spawns.  All players present at the time of spawning should be included in the compromise.  Such compromises can be reached via /random or various other compromises in which <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> all</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> parties are in agreement. <br>
<br>
If a player-devised compromise cannot be met with all parties present...<br>
<br>
2) VI Compromise: An EQCSR should be contacted to mandate a binding compromise.  All players must abide by this agreement or face disciplinary action witnessed by the EQCSR.<br>
<br>
These are not <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> my</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> opinions, but they are the actual rules which we abide by when playing this game.  We agree to them each and every time we log on.  I'm not brown-nosing VI either.  I'm just stating policies and trying to reach an understanding so that we may utilize them to our benefit, as they were put in place for that exact reason.<br>
<br>
We may not all agree on the rules, but they are what we have to work with.  We have an opportunity to reach compromises of our own device, but if they cannot be met then we have an independent third-party (VI) who can step in and assist us.  My feeling on contacting an EQCSR isn't to get somebody in trouble, or to give myself an advantage, but to get somebody not involved into the decision-making process.<br>
<br>
Last note, no matter how much we may dislike the rules and how many ideas we have to improve upon them, VI will not change them at this point in time. No matter how many players or servers agree on such things as lists, calenders, camp claimings, etc, they have written a firm rule which is pretty much set in stone.<br>
<br>
I hope this helps us, for in the future we will be faced with many more Ragefires and similar situations may happen.<br>
<br>
